        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Sisig is a Kapampangan word and the dish is a Pampanga export. Before the sizzling-plate bar food you eat in Manila, sisig was pig-head meat boiled, grilled, chopped, and dressed with calamansi and chili. Aling Lucing of Angeles is widely credited with the sizzling version sometime in the 1970s along the railroad tracks of Crossing. The trail below walks through the spots that still serve sisig the closest to the original.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-day eat-around in Angeles, Pampanga, around two hours north of Quezon City via NLEX. Bring an empty stomach and stretchy pants. Tara, the kwento starts at Aling Lucing.</p>
<h2>Aling Lucing Sisig</h2>
<p>Aling Lucing Sisig still operates along the railroad tracks in Angeles, the same area where Lucia Cunanan is said to have first served the sizzling version. The plates are unpretentious, the chopping board is well-used, and the sisig itself is closer to the original than the mayo-and-egg versions you see in Manila chains. Order the regular sisig, a side of garlic rice, and a bottle of San Mig Light. The meat has texture, the calamansi sharpens it, and the sizzling plate keeps the bottom crisp.</p>
<p>Open from late morning until evening. Cash is the safer bet. The shop is humble and you sit on benches under a tin roof; the kwento of the place is the draw, not the interior.</p>
<h2>Mila's Tokwa't Baboy</h2>
<p>Two blocks from Aling Lucing, Mila's serves tokwa't baboy that some Kapampangans say predates the sizzling sisig. Fried pork ear and tofu in a soy-vinegar dressing with chopped chili, the dish is what Aling Lucing reportedly started with before she added the sizzling plate. Eat it standing or sitting at a plastic table. The portion is small; share two orders between two people.</p>
<h2>Aling Lucing Branch on McArthur Highway</h2>
<p>The family runs a second branch on McArthur Highway with table service and aircon. The sisig is the same; the experience is calmer if you do not want the railroad atmosphere. Use this branch if you are bringing elders or visiting in the heat of midday.</p>
<h2>Atching Lillian Borromeo (Mexico, Pampanga)</h2>
<p>If you have a car and an extra hour, drive 25 minutes from Angeles to Mexico town to visit Atching Lillian Borromeo, a Kapampangan culinary historian. She runs cooking classes from her home kitchen by appointment and will walk you through Kapampangan dishes most travelers never hear about. Book a week ahead. Not sisig-specific but the wider Kapampangan kitchen makes more sense after the visit.</p>
<h2>Everybody's Cafe, San Fernando</h2>
<p>Drive 20 minutes south to San Fernando city for lunch or merienda at Everybody's Cafe, one of the oldest Kapampangan restaurants still operating since 1946. Their sisig is the bigger menu draw plus betute (stuffed frog), camaru (crickets), and morcon. The interior is old-school, the plating is clean, and the kitchen still uses the family recipes.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Buses from Cubao to Dau terminal in Mabalacat run every 15 minutes. Around two hours with light traffic. From Dau take a jeepney or tricycle to Crossing, Angeles. If you drive, NLEX to Dau exit then McArthur Highway south. Parking is easier on weekday mornings.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Weekday lunch is the calmest window. Weekend evenings draw the full Angeles dining crowd. Avoid Holy Week and the period around Sinukwan Festival in December when the carinderias close or run on short hours.</p>
<p>Sisig is not the most photogenic dish but the Angeles version has the kwento, the texture, and the calamansi-and-chili bite that the chain versions cannot copy. Eat where Aling Lucing started and you will taste the difference.</p>
