    // 3. BETIS WOODCARVING
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/betis-woodcarving-pampanga',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Betis Woodcarving: A Heritage Visit in Guagua, Pampanga',
        'slug' => 'betis-woodcarving-heritage-guagua-pampanga',
        'excerpt' => 'Betis is the woodcarving town of Pampanga and home to the painted-ceiling church locals call the Sistine of the Philippines. Here is a calm half-day visit.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Betis is a barangay of Guagua, Pampanga, and it has been the woodcarving town of the Philippines for over two centuries. The carvers here supplied the religious images, the choir stalls, and the retablos for churches across Luzon. The craft survives today in family workshops along the main road, and the town's own church holds one of the most-photographed painted ceilings in the country.</p>
<p>Guagua is around two hours from Quezon City via NLEX. A half-day visit pairs well with a Pampanga food trail. Tara, the kwento starts at the church.</p>
<h2>Betis Church (St. James the Apostle Parish)</h2>
<p>The Betis Church was built in 1660 and the present structure was rebuilt after a fire in the late 1700s. The exterior is stone and the interior is the surprise: every inch of the ceiling is painted with biblical scenes, the apse is gilded, and the side altars carry retablos carved by Betis masters. Local guides call it the Sistine Chapel of the Philippines. The comparison is generous but the painted ceiling does hold up to a long look.</p>
<p>Free entry. Modest dress. The church is active so plan your visit between masses. A small donation supports the parish.</p>
<h2>Local Woodcarving Workshops</h2>
<p>Walk or tricycle along the main Betis road and you will pass several family workshops with finished pieces and chisels still in motion. The shops carve furniture, religious images, doors, and frames. Most welcome visitors who are quiet and respectful; ask permission before taking photos of the carvers at work. Prices for finished pieces start in the low thousands for small items and climb high for life-size santos.</p>
<p>A few names to ask for: Castor Lim and his apprentices; Willy Layug, a well-known image-maker whose workshop has supplied parishes across the country. Smaller carvers along Sto. Cristo Street produce the supply chain that finishes furniture for Manila buyers.</p>
<h2>Lunch in Guagua</h2>
<p>For lunch try Capili's BBQ in Guagua town center or any of the local carinderias along the plaza. Order Kapampangan dishes that travel well: bringhe, lechon kawali, and tortang talong. If you want a fuller meal, drive 25 minutes to Apag Marangle in Mexico, Pampanga.</p>
<h2>Other Heritage Stops Nearby</h2>
<p>Bacolor is 15 minutes away and the town buried halfway by Mt. Pinatubo lahar. The Bacolor Church still has its bell tower poking through the lahar-raised plaza, a strange and quiet sight. The Casa de Don Cesar Suing in Bacolor is one of the surviving heritage houses if you can arrange a visit.</p>
<p>Lubao Church, another half hour, is the second oldest church in Pampanga and a calm stop on the way back to Manila if you want to extend the heritage line.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila take any bus heading to Olongapo or Iba and ask to be dropped at Guagua. From Dau in Angeles, take a jeepney south to Guagua, around 45 minutes. If you drive, NLEX to San Fernando exit then MacArthur Highway south to Guagua.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Late January is the Apung Iro Festival (San Pedro Apostol patronal feast on the Guagua river), worth catching for the procession but louder than the half-day calm visit described here. November to early December is dry, cooler, and quiet at the workshops. Avoid mid-summer noon visits to the church; the windows are small and the heat builds.</p>
<p>Betis is the woodcarving town where the chisels still come down on hardwood every day. A morning at the church and an hour at one workshop is enough to leave with a different picture of how Philippine sacred art was made.</p>
