    // 4. BULACAN ENSAYMADA MALOLOS
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/ensaymada-malolos-bulacan',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Ensaymada and Pancit Marilao Route in Bulacan',
        'slug' => 'ensaymada-pancit-marilao-route-bulacan',
        'excerpt' => 'Malolos has been baking ensaymada since the Spanish era. This is a calm day trip pairing the Malolos bakeries with pancit Marilao for an old-Bulacan food run.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bulacan is the next province north of Metro Manila, an hour by NLEX, and the home of two long-running food specialties that most travelers race past on their way to Pampanga. Malolos has the ensaymada bakeries that go back to the Spanish era and the early-Republic Aguinaldo years. Marilao is the original home of pancit Marilao, a dry stir-fried bihon with a generous load of pork and bagnet bits. The two towns together make a calm one-day food run from Manila.</p>
<p>This is a DIY route by car or by bus to Malolos then tricycle to Marilao. Tara, the kwento starts in Malolos.</p>
<h2>Eurobake Malolos</h2>
<p>Eurobake on Estrella Street, Malolos is one of the bakeries locals will name first when you ask about ensaymada. The version here is the traditional Spanish-Filipino kind: brioche-style dough, butter, sugar, and a layer of grated quesong puti. Some lines top with cheddar; the classic version with kesong puti is the order to get. The bakery opens early and the morning batch sells through by mid-morning on weekends.</p>
<h2>Patisserie de Malolos</h2>
<p>A few blocks away, Patisserie de Malolos has a calmer cafe layout with seating and coffee. Their ensaymada has a softer crumb and they also do empanada de kaliskis, the flaky empanada specific to Bulacan. Order one of each and a cup of coffee. The empanada de kaliskis is the bakery's quieter showpiece, with layers like a croissant and a sweet pork-and-egg filling.</p>
<h2>Barasoain Church</h2>
<p>Walk five minutes from the bakery row to Barasoain Church, the site of the First Philippine Republic and one of the most historically loaded buildings in Bulacan. Free entry. The small museum behind the church explains the 1898 Malolos Congress and the drafting of the Malolos Constitution. A 45-minute stop is enough.</p>
<h2>Malolos Cathedral and the Heritage District</h2>
<p>Across the river is the Malolos Cathedral, the seat of the diocese, and the heritage district with the old casa houses of the Malolos women who petitioned for the right to learn Spanish (the ones Jose Rizal wrote a letter to in 1889). A walking loop of the cathedral, the Casa Real, and the heritage houses takes around an hour. Tricycle drivers around the cathedral will quote a flat fee for a 60-minute heritage drive-by if you do not want to walk in the heat.</p>
<h2>Lunch in Marilao: Pancit Marilao</h2>
<p>Drive 25 minutes south from Malolos to Marilao for the pancit. Pancit Marilao is a dry rice-noodle dish, originally made with bihon, dressed with kalabasa sauce, topped with chicharon and bagnet, and seasoned with calamansi. The original carinderia stalls are scattered along the Marilao town plaza area. Mang Lino's and the unnamed stalls near the Marilao Church both serve good versions. Order one bilao to share.</p>
<h2>Bulacan Longganisa</h2>
<p>Bulacan longganisa is sweeter and shorter than Vigan or Lucban; the closest carinderia to the Marilao church will have it on the breakfast plate. Buy a half kilo to bring home from any of the meat shops along the highway between Marilao and Meycauayan.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cubao or Pasay take any northbound bus and ask to be dropped at Malolos. Around one hour by bus on a weekday morning. From Malolos to Marilao is a 25-minute jeepney or tricycle ride. If you drive, NLEX to Marilao exit then north to Malolos; return south to Marilao for lunch.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Weekday mornings are the calmest for the bakeries and the heritage walk. The third week of January is the Malolos Town Fiesta with parades and food fairs; loud but festive. Avoid Holy Week when the bakeries run on short hours.</p>
<p>Bulacan is the Manila food day-trip most travelers skip on the way to Pampanga. The ensaymada and the pancit alone make the round trip worth it.</p>
