    // 5. LUCBAN KAKANIN
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatseralovers.com/lucban-kakanin-quezon',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsera Lovers',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Kakanin Route in Lucban, Quezon',
        'slug' => 'kakanin-route-lucban-quezon',
        'excerpt' => 'Lucban is famous for Pahiyas and pancit habhab, but the town also runs deep on kakanin. Here is a calm half-day trail through the rice cake makers of Lucban.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Lucban, Quezon is best known for the Pahiyas Festival in May and for pancit habhab eaten on a banana leaf. The town also runs a deep kakanin (rice cake) tradition: suman sa lihiya, broas, tikoy, kalamay, and the egg-yolk yema that Quezon makers turn out by the thousand for Manila. This is a calm half-day kakanin route built around weekday mornings.</p>
<p>Lucban is around three hours from Quezon City via SLEX and Pagsanjan. A car or a bus to Lucena then jeepney to Lucban works. Tara, the kwento starts at the public market.</p>
<h2>Lucban Public Market</h2>
<p>Start at the Lucban Public Market on a Sunday or any market day. The kakanin row at the back of the wet market sells suman sa lihiya wrapped in palm fronds, puto seko, broas, and uraro. Ask the vendor to slice a suman for a quick taste; pair it with the brown sugar muscovado syrup the vendors sell beside the rice cakes.</p>
<h2>Suman Sa Lihiya: The Lucban Version</h2>
<p>Lucban suman is made with glutinous rice soaked in lihiya (lye water from burnt palm fronds), wrapped in coconut leaves, and steamed. The result is a denser, more amber-colored suman than the white tagalog version. Eat it with the muscovado syrup or with niyog. A bundle of 10 costs less than a sit-down meal.</p>
<h2>Broas and Uraro Bakeries</h2>
<p>Lucban broas are crisp, ladyfinger-style biscuits good with coffee. The town has small bakeries that still produce them by hand. Uraro is the arrowroot cookie that melts on contact with hot calamansi tea. Both keep well and make easy pasalubong. Ask any tricycle driver for the broas bakery on Reguindin Street.</p>
<h2>Yema Cake and Sapin-Sapin Houses</h2>
<p>Yema is not from Lucban itself but several Lucban home kitchens produce yema candies wrapped in cellophane. The brown sugar yema with cashew is the version to bring home. Sapin-sapin (the layered purple, white, and yellow rice cake) is made in a few of the older households around Lucban and sold at the market by midday.</p>
<h2>Pancit Habhab (For the Salty Break)</h2>
<p>Between kakanin stops, take a habhab break. Pancit habhab is miki noodles stir-fried with pork, liver, and vegetables, served on a piece of banana leaf, and eaten without utensils by tilting the leaf into your mouth. Old Center Panciteria along the plaza is the classic stop. One serving is small; order two and share.</p>
<h2>Kamay Ni Hesus Shrine (Light Heritage Side)</h2>
<p>If you are not Pahiyas-bound, walk or tricycle up to the Kamay Ni Hesus shrine on the slopes of Mt. Banahaw for a non-food stop. The Stations of the Cross climb 305 steps to a Risen Christ statue at the top. The view of Lucban and the surrounding rice fields is calm and clean. Half an hour to climb and rest.</p>
<h2>Lucban Church (San Luis Obispo de Tolosa)</h2>
<p>The Lucban Church, built in stone in 1738, is the parish at the center of every Pahiyas procession. The plaza outside is where Pahiyas houses set up the kiping-decorated facades each May. On a non-Pahiyas day the plaza is calm and good for kakanin-eating on a bench.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila take a bus to Lucena (around three hours), then a jeepney to Lucban (one hour, scenic mountain road). If you drive, SLEX to Pagsanjan then mountain road to Lucban. The mountain stretch is winding; first-timer drivers should leave early.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any month except May Pahiyas week if you want the calm kakanin route. Pahiyas is loud, packed, and the focus shifts to the decorated houses; come back another month for a slow eating day. Sundays and town market days have the fullest kakanin selection.</p>
<p>The kakanin of Lucban is the quiet half of the town's food identity. A Sunday morning at the market is enough to leave with two bags of suman and a different understanding of Quezon's rice-cake tradition.</p>
