    // 7. BICOL LAING TRAIL
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/laing-trail-camalig-albay',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Laing Trail in Camalig, Albay',
        'slug' => 'laing-trail-camalig-albay',
        'excerpt' => 'Laing is the Bicolano dish of dried taro leaves braised in coconut cream and chili. Camalig in Albay is the home base. Here is a calm half-day trail.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Laing is the Bicolano dish of dried taro leaves braised in coconut cream with chili, ginger, and small smoky bits of pork or dried fish. The home base of laing is Camalig, Albay, the town at the foot of Mt. Mayon where taro grows along the volcanic slopes. This is a calm half-day route through the Camalig laing makers and one of the most overlooked Bicol food trips.</p>
<p>Camalig is a 30-minute drive west of Legazpi. The route works as a side loop on a Mayon trip. Tara, the kwento starts at the Camalig public market.</p>
<h2>Camalig Public Market</h2>
<p>The market is small and the laing row sits near the cooked-food stalls. Most stalls sell laing by the kilo in plastic packs, room-temperature for take-out and reheating. Ask for a tablespoon taste before you commit; the spice levels vary by maker. Some lean creamier, some lean dryer. The standard order is a half kilo packed for the road.</p>
<h2>1st Colonial Grill (Legazpi)</h2>
<p>Drive back to Legazpi for 1st Colonial Grill, the restaurant that built a calm reputation on Bicol comfort food. Order the laing plate as a side, the pinangat (taro leaves wrapped tight around fish or meat), and the Bicol Express. Their sili ice cream comes after; chili-laced cream that is more interesting than it sounds. Two people can split four plates here for a full Bicol survey.</p>
<h2>Sumlang Lake (Light Mayon Stop)</h2>
<p>Between Camalig and Legazpi, Sumlang Lake is a calm 15-minute stop with bamboo raft rides and a clean view of Mayon on a clear day. Free entry; the rafts are paid per ride. The lake is quieter than Cagsawa Ruins and the food kiosks serve passable laing if you want to taste it lakeside.</p>
<h2>Cagsawa Ruins</h2>
<p>The Cagsawa Ruins are a 10-minute drive from Camalig and the standard Mayon photo stop. The half-buried church belfry is the foreground for the Mayon cone. Pair with a laing-stuffed pandesal from any of the kiosks at the parking area for a road-style merienda.</p>
<h2>Pinangat: The Stuffed Cousin of Laing</h2>
<p>Pinangat is not laing. It is taro leaves wrapped tightly around fish, shrimp, or pork, then simmered in coconut cream. Camalig is also a pinangat town. Buy a few wrapped bundles from the market or from any roadside stall labeled "pinangat sa Camalig." They travel cold for a day.</p>
<h2>Spice Levels and Variants</h2>
<p>Bicol laing leans hotter than Manila restaurant versions. Tell the maker if you want it mild (kabaitan), medium (regular), or hot (maanghang); they will adjust the chili. Some makers add tinapa or dried squid for a smokier flavor; others stick to pork. Buy from two makers to compare.</p>
<h2>What to Bring Home</h2>
<p>Vacuum-packed laing keeps frozen for a month and chilled for four days. Camalig makers will pack two-kilo blocks for travelers heading back to Manila. Add a bag of pili nuts (the Bicol regional nut) from any roadside stall and you have a full Bicol pasalubong bag.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Legazpi from Manila in one hour. From Legazpi airport, a tricycle to Camalig is around 45 minutes. By bus from Cubao, the trip is 10 to 12 hours overnight; ask to be dropped at Legazpi terminal then take a jeepney west to Camalig.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from January to May are the cleanest for Mayon views and for sun-drying taro leaves at the makers' workshops. The Magayon Festival in May is the Albay food season; the laing makers expand their stalls. Avoid the typhoon stretch from August to November when the road conditions vary.</p>
<p>Laing is one of those dishes that tastes different at the source. A morning in Camalig and a lunch at 1st Colonial Grill is enough to rewrite the menu of Bicol food in your head.</p>
