    // 10. SILI ICE CREAM
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/sili-ice-cream-1st-colonial-legazpi',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Sili Ice Cream in Legazpi: A Bicol Dessert Note',
        'slug' => 'sili-ice-cream-legazpi-bicol-dessert',
        'excerpt' => 'Bicol turned chili into a dessert. Sili ice cream and pili ice cream are the regional ice cream pairs to try in Legazpi. Here is the calm tasting note.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Sili ice cream is the Legazpi dessert that became one of the regional pride moments of Bicol. Cream, sugar, and a controlled load of siling labuyo (Philippine bird's-eye chili) churned into a scoop that starts sweet then opens into a chili glow at the back of the throat. The original is from 1st Colonial Grill in Legazpi, and the regional ice cream tradition there has expanded into other Bicol flavors worth tasting in a single afternoon.</p>
<p>This is a short tasting note for travelers visiting Legazpi for Mayon, Cagsawa, or the laing trail. The ice cream stop is a 30-minute side trip. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>1st Colonial Grill (Legazpi)</h2>
<p>1st Colonial Grill on Daraga or at SM Legazpi serves the original sili ice cream. The flavor menu rotates but the regular lineup includes sili (chili), pili nut, malunggay, tinutong (toasted rice), and ube. Order the four-flavor sampler and pair with their pili tart or with a clean glass of water.</p>
<h2>The Heat Curve</h2>
<p>The sili ice cream does not announce the chili in the first bite. The sweetness leads, the cream coats the tongue, then the chili climbs slow through the second swallow. By the third spoon the glow is steady. The version is controlled; you can finish a scoop without trouble. Children handle it surprisingly well; the adults are the ones who scream first.</p>
<h2>Pili Ice Cream</h2>
<p>The pili nut is the Bicol regional nut, fattier and more buttery than cashew. Pili ice cream uses pili paste and chopped roasted pili. The flavor is closer to brown butter pecan than to peanut. Worth ordering even if you skip the sili.</p>
<h2>Tinutong (Toasted Rice) Ice Cream</h2>
<p>Tinutong is the kanin tutong (toasted rice) flavor. The taste is roasty, slightly burnt, and surprisingly elegant. Good for diners who do not want chili or sugar overload.</p>
<h2>Malunggay Ice Cream</h2>
<p>Malunggay (moringa) ice cream is green, mild, and herbal. The flavor is gentle and pairs well with a pili tart. Not the headliner but a calm scoop.</p>
<h2>Other Bicol Sweets to Pair</h2>
<p>Pair the ice cream stop with a box of pili tart (J Emmanuel or any Albay bakery) and a small jar of pili caramel. The Bicol sweet bag is heavy on pili and not much else; that is a feature, not a limitation.</p>
<h2>Spice Tolerance Notes</h2>
<p>If you are sensitive to chili, order a half scoop of sili and a full scoop of pili. The half scoop is enough to experience the curve without committing the full chili climb. If you came for the spice, order two scoops of sili and a glass of milk on standby.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>1st Colonial Grill has branches in Daraga, SM Legazpi, and Ayala Embarcadero. The Daraga branch is near Cagsawa Ruins. The SM Legazpi branch is the easiest after a city walk.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any month. The afternoon merienda window from 3 to 5 PM is the calmest. Tag the visit to the end of a laing day for the contrast between savory chili and sweet chili.</p>
<h2>What to Bring Home</h2>
<p>Sili ice cream does not travel home; it melts before Manila. Buy pili tarts, pili candies, and a jar of pili praline instead. The ice cream is for on-site only.</p>
<p>Sili ice cream is the Bicol experiment that earned its regional fame. A 30-minute stop at 1st Colonial is enough to leave with a sweet-spicy memory of Legazpi.</p>
