    // 11. LA PAZ BATCHOY DEEP DIVE
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/la-paz-batchoy-iloilo-deep-dive',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'La Paz Batchoy in Iloilo: Three Bowls, One Origin',
        'slug' => 'la-paz-batchoy-iloilo-three-bowls-origin',
        'excerpt' => 'La Paz batchoy is the Iloilo noodle soup with pork organs, chicharon, and a deep stock. Here is the deeper origin walk through three of the original makers.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>La Paz batchoy is the noodle soup that put La Paz district of Iloilo City on the national menu. Miki noodles in a deep pork-bone stock, topped with chicharon, pork liver, kidney, intestines, and a generous sprinkle of fried garlic. The dish started in La Paz Market in the 1930s and three families still serve their versions: Deco's, Ted's, and Netong's. Each tells the origin story a little differently. This is a calm half-day route through all three bowls.</p>
<p>The walk works as a slow morning eat-around in Iloilo City. Tara, the kwento starts at La Paz Public Market.</p>
<h2>Netong's Original Lapaz Batchoy</h2>
<p>Netong's sits inside La Paz Market itself, on the second floor near the dry goods. The shop is the most market-style of the three: small, basic seating, no aircon, real wet-market sounds. The batchoy here is heavier on innards and the stock is darker. Order the regular batchoy and a side of bottled San Mig. Open from breakfast onward.</p>
<h2>Ted's Old Timer Lapaz Batchoy</h2>
<p>Ted's expanded into a national chain but the original branch is on Huervana Street near La Paz Market. The version here is balanced and traveler-friendly: less innards, more pork, cleaner broth. Ted's also serves rice plates and siopao. Useful as the middle stop on a three-bowl walk because the milder broth resets the palate.</p>
<h2>Deco's Original Lapaz Batchoy</h2>
<p>Deco's is the family that several Iloilo historians credit as the first batchoy maker in the 1930s. The original Deco's still operates near La Paz Market. Their version has the cleanest broth of the three and uses thinner noodles. The chicharon is generous and the garlic is the strongest. End the three-bowl walk here.</p>
<h2>How To Pace Three Bowls</h2>
<p>Three full bowls in one morning is a heavy commitment. The strategy: order a half-portion at Netong's and Ted's, full portion at Deco's (or whichever is your favorite). Walk between the shops to reset. Drink water between bowls; the stock is salt-forward. The whole walk takes around two hours.</p>
<h2>What Else to Order</h2>
<p>Each shop has a siopao and pancit menu. Pancit Molo is the Iloilo sibling to batchoy (wonton soup, not stir-fried noodles) and worth tasting at one of the shops or at a separate Molo restaurant. Pair the batchoy walk with a Molo lunch for the full Iloilo noodle survey.</p>
<h2>La Paz Market Itself</h2>
<p>Walk through La Paz Market between the bowls. The wet section sells fresh seafood from the Iloilo coast; the dry section has muscovado sugar, mango bars, biscocho, and butterscotch from local bakeries. Buy biscocho from any of the stalls; it is the Iloilo bread snack that pairs with morning coffee.</p>
<h2>The Heritage Side</h2>
<p>La Paz also holds the La Paz Church, a stone parish from the Spanish era, and a small heritage row along Huervana. After three bowls of batchoy, a slow walk through the streets is the natural way to settle the stomach.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Iloilo from Manila in one hour and 15 minutes. From Iloilo airport, a 20-minute taxi or Grab to La Paz district. By boat from Bacolod, the FastCat or OceanJet crossing takes around one hour to Iloilo port.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Weekday mornings from 8 to 10 AM are the calmest at all three shops. The fourth week of January is Dinagyang Festival in Iloilo and the city is at full volume; come for the energy if you can handle the crowd. Avoid Holy Week when the shops run on short hours.</p>
<p>La Paz batchoy is one of the regional Filipino dishes that tastes the way it was meant to only in its hometown. A three-bowl morning is the cleanest way to taste why.</p>
