    // 13. GUIMARAS MANGO FARM
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatseralovers.com/guimaras-mango-farm-circuit',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsera Lovers',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Guimaras Mango Farm Circuit',
        'slug' => 'guimaras-mango-farm-circuit-iloilo',
        'excerpt' => 'Guimaras grows the sweetest mangoes in the country. Here is a calm one-day circuit through the mango farms and the dried mango factory.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Guimaras is the small island province across the strait from Iloilo City and the home of what the National Mango Research Center certifies as one of the sweetest mango varieties in the world. The island runs a mango farm circuit, a dried mango factory, and a few calm beach stops on the same day. This is a one-day route from Iloilo for travelers who want to follow the mango from tree to dried slice.</p>
<p>From Iloilo, the boat to Jordan port in Guimaras takes 15 minutes. Tara, the kwento starts at Jordan port.</p>
<h2>Jordan Port</h2>
<p>The wharf at Jordan is the main entry point. Tricycle drivers cluster at the exit offering hop-on, hop-off circuits for the day. Negotiate a flat rate for a five-stop tour. Most drivers know the mango farms, the trappist monastery, and the beaches by heart.</p>
<h2>National Mango Research and Development Center</h2>
<p>The NMRDC in Jordan is a working research facility that develops grafting techniques and pest control for Philippine mango varieties. Visits are by appointment for student groups; individual travelers can sometimes do drop-in tours if a staff member is available. Even a parking-lot walkthrough is informative; the demo orchard is visible from the road.</p>
<h2>Mango Farm Stops</h2>
<p>The island has several mango farms open to visitors. The Oro Verde Mango Farm offers tours during fruiting season (April to June). The drive winds through orchard rows and the farm staff explain the grafting, the spraying, and the harvesting. Eat mangoes straight from the tree if the season is right.</p>
<h2>The Pit Stop Mango Pizza</h2>
<p>The Pit Stop is the Guimaras food landmark that built a quiet fame on mango pizza. Crust topped with cream sauce, fresh mangoes, and cheese. Sounds strange, tastes worth ordering. The restaurant also serves mango shakes, mango ribs, and traditional Iloilo plates.</p>
<h2>Trappist Monastery and Souvenir Shop</h2>
<p>The Trappist Monastery on a hillside in Jordan runs a souvenir shop with mango products produced by the monks: mango jam, mango bars, mango ketchup, mango wine. The monks live a quiet contemplative life and visitors are welcome at the shop and the small chapel.</p>
<h2>Dried Mango Factory</h2>
<p>Visit a dried mango factory in Jordan or Buenavista. Some factories run tours by appointment. The process: pick, peel, slice, blanch, dry, pack. The Guimaras dried mango is yellower and chewier than the Cebu commercial brands; the difference is the slow-drying.</p>
<h2>Smallest Plaza in the World</h2>
<p>Guimaras claims the smallest plaza in the world, the Plaza of Jordan town, around 60 square meters. A photo-and-laugh stop; the claim is humble and the plaza is real.</p>
<h2>Alubihod Beach</h2>
<p>End the day at Alubihod Beach, the white-sand beach 30 minutes from Jordan port. Day-tour fee is small; the sand is fine, the water is calm, and the small island hopping circuit to Turtle Island and SEAFDEC is available. Stay for sunset before the last boat back to Iloilo.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Iloilo City take the boat from Parola Wharf to Jordan, Guimaras. Boats run every 30 minutes from 5 AM to 6 PM. The crossing takes 15 minutes.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>April to June is mango season. The fruit is fresh, the farms are active, and the prices for buying mangoes by the box are at their lowest. The annual Manggahan Festival is in May with parades and mango-eating contests. Off-season visits still work for the dried mango factory and the beaches.</p>
<p>Guimaras is a calm one-day side trip from Iloilo with a sweet payoff. A box of fresh mangoes for the boat ride home is the natural conclusion.</p>
