    // 15. PUSO MAKING
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/puso-making-cebu',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Puso Making: The Hanging Rice of Cebu',
        'slug' => 'puso-making-hanging-rice-cebu',
        'excerpt' => 'Puso is the woven coconut-leaf rice pouch that pairs with Cebu lechon. Here is a calm note on where to watch it made and how to order it right.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Puso is the woven coconut-leaf rice pouch that hangs in bunches at every Cebu lechon stall and barbecue strip. The rice is sealed inside a heart-shaped woven pouch, dropped into boiling water, and steamed to a clean, slightly aromatic finish. Puso predates the colonial era and remains the everyday rice format for Cebuano food culture. This is a calm note on where to see it made and how to order it right.</p>
<p>The puso-making weavers work in the public markets of Cebu City, Carcar, and Talisay. A short side trip during a lechon trail covers the kwento. Tara, here is the walk.</p>
<h2>What Puso Is</h2>
<p>Puso means "heart" in Cebuano. The pouch is woven from young coconut leaves into a tight diamond or heart shape, filled halfway with raw rice, and tied. The pouches are boiled in batches; the woven leaf gives the rice a faint coconut aroma and a denser, more compact texture than steamed rice. Eat one or two per meal as a side; tear the leaf with your fingers and pour the rice onto your plate.</p>
<h2>Carcar Public Market</h2>
<p>The Carcar Public Market has a puso section near the lechon row. The weavers sit on low stools with a pile of coconut leaves, weaving pouches at a rhythm of about 20 per minute. Watch for five minutes and the pattern becomes clear: fold, weave, fold, tie. Ask permission before taking photos; most weavers are friendly and used to travelers.</p>
<h2>Larsian (Cebu City Barbecue Strip)</h2>
<p>Larsian on Fuente Osmena is the barbecue strip of Cebu City with grilled pork skewers, chicken inasal, and trays of puso hanging from above. The puso here is smaller and the count is by piece. Order three puso per person for a proper barbecue dinner. The cost per puso is so low that travelers often miss the value; in Cebu, puso is the rice and the rice is puso.</p>
<h2>Sutukil Strip (Mactan)</h2>
<p>The Sutukil restaurants on Mactan Island (named for sugba, tula, and kilaw) all serve puso. Order grilled fish (sugba), fish soup (tula), and fish ceviche (kilaw) with two puso per person. The Mactan setting near Lapu-Lapu Shrine is a longer trip but a clean three-course Cebuano meal.</p>
<h2>How to Eat Puso</h2>
<p>Tear the woven leaf with your fingers along the seam. The rice falls onto your plate in a heart-shaped mound. Eat with your hands (kamayan) for the full Cebu experience, or use a fork and spoon. The leaf is discarded; only the rice is eaten.</p>
<h2>Why Puso Persists</h2>
<p>Puso is portable. Workers carry them to the fields, the fishing boat, or the construction site without spilling. It is also a non-plastic packaging built from the same trees that produce the coconuts and the leaves. In a country that runs on rice, puso is the engineering solution that predates Tupperware.</p>
<h2>Buying Puso for the Road</h2>
<p>Puso travels well for half a day at room temperature. The leaf keeps the rice from drying out. Buy a dozen for a road trip across Cebu; the rice will hold until lunch. Reheat by steaming for two minutes if needed.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Larsian is in central Cebu City. Carcar Public Market is one hour south by bus from the South Bus Terminal. The Sutukil strip is on Mactan, 30 minutes east of Cebu City across the bridge.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any time. Lunch and dinner are the natural windows. Sinulog Festival in January is the calendar peak but the puso supply holds because the weavers run on overtime.</p>
<p>Puso is the rice format that most travelers eat without thinking about. A morning at the Carcar Public Market with the weavers explains why Cebu food culture stays anchored to the leaf.</p>
