    // 16. CEBU DRIED MANGO
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatseralovers.com/cebu-dried-mango-trail',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsera Lovers',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Dried Mango Trail in Cebu',
        'slug' => 'dried-mango-trail-cebu',
        'excerpt' => 'Cebu turned dried mangoes into a national pasalubong icon. Here is a calm tasting trail through the brands and factories that built the category.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Dried mangoes are the pasalubong most travelers bring home from Cebu. The category is built on Philippine carabao mangoes (the yellow ovate variety), sliced thin, sugared lightly, dried slow, and packed in resealable pouches. Cebu is the production capital. This is a calm tasting trail through the major brands and the factory tours.</p>
<p>The trail covers central Cebu and the Mactan airport export hubs. Two hours and three brands is enough for the side trip. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Profood (7D)</h2>
<p>Profood, makers of the 7D brand, is the largest dried mango producer in the country and the brand most travelers know from airport gift shops. The 7D version is consistent: thin slices, balanced sweetness, clean chew. The brand also makes dried pineapple, dried papaya, and mango juice drinks. Buy at the SM, Ayala, or airport pasalubong shops.</p>
<h2>Cebu Brands Compared</h2>
<p>Beyond 7D, Cebu has Philippine Brand, Profruits, and several smaller labels. Philippine Brand is sweeter and thicker. Profruits is the no-sugar-added line for diabetic travelers. The smaller brands at the Carbon Market and Taboan Public Market sell loose-pack dried mangoes by the kilo at the lowest prices; quality varies.</p>
<h2>Taboan Public Market</h2>
<p>Taboan in Cebu City is the pasalubong public market where loose-pack dried mangoes, danggit, dried squid, and mango bars are sold by weight. The dried mango section is in the dry-goods area. Try a slice from two or three stalls before committing to a kilo. The taste varies by maker; some lean tarter, some lean sweeter.</p>
<h2>Mango Tart Variant</h2>
<p>Beyond the standard dried slices, Cebu makers produce mango tart strips: shorter, chewier, candied bars. Goldilocks and several smaller bakeshops carry them as merienda items. Sweeter than dried mango, closer to candy.</p>
<h2>Mango Juice and Mango Bars</h2>
<p>Profood and Philippine Brand also produce mango juice drinks and mango bars (compressed, thick mango candy in foil wraps). Both are good road snacks. The mango bars predate the dried mango category and were the original pasalubong from Cebu before 7D scaled.</p>
<h2>Cebuano Quality Cues</h2>
<p>What separates good dried mangoes: color (golden yellow, not pale or dark), texture (chewy but not leathery), sweetness (balanced, not cloying), and origin (carabao mango, not Indian or Australian variety). The premium brands say "carabao mango" on the pack. Lower-priced versions sometimes mix varieties.</p>
<h2>How Much to Bring Home</h2>
<p>One kilo of dried mango weighs around 250 grams of original fresh fruit and fits in a small bag. Travelers usually buy two to three kilos for office sharing. The product is dry, vacuum-packed, and survives a long flight without refrigeration.</p>
<h2>Airport Pasalubong Run</h2>
<p>Mactan-Cebu International Airport has full pasalubong shops post-security. If you forgot to buy in the city, the airport prices are higher but the selection is complete. Allow 30 minutes before boarding for the run.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Profood factory tours are by appointment for groups; check ahead. Taboan Public Market is in Cebu City and reachable by taxi or Grab. The Mactan airport pasalubong shops are at departures.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Year-round; the dried mango supply is stable. Mango fresh season is April to June and prices for the dried product sometimes dip post-season. Avoid buying loose-pack from Taboan if you cannot finish within a month; the home-pack moisture content is higher than the commercial brands.</p>
<p>Cebu dried mango is the pasalubong category that turned a regional fruit into a national gift. A short tasting morning across two or three brands is enough to find the version you prefer.</p>
