    // 17. BOHOL UBE HALAYA
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/bohol-ube-halaya-peanut-kisses',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Ube Halaya and Peanut Kisses: A Bohol Sweet Run',
        'slug' => 'ube-halaya-peanut-kisses-bohol-sweet-run',
        'excerpt' => 'Bohol is known for tarsiers and chocolate hills but the sweet pasalubong scene runs deep. Here is a calm trail through ube halaya and peanut kisses makers.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bohol is the Chocolate Hills and tarsiers province for most travelers, but the pasalubong category in Bohol holds two sweet anchors that locals defend with pride. Ube halaya from Bohol uses local purple yam and carabao milk for a denser, deeper version than the Manila supermarket pots. Peanut kisses, the bite-size peanut meringues from Dauis on Panglao, are the sweet take-home stack. This is a calm half-day food trail.</p>
<p>The route covers Tagbilaran and Dauis on Panglao. Tara, the kwento starts at the Tagbilaran pasalubong row.</p>
<h2>Bohol Bee Farm Pasalubong Shop</h2>
<p>Bohol Bee Farm in Dauis on Panglao sells the cleanest commercial ube halaya in the province. The farm uses organic purple yam grown on the farm, fresh carabao milk, and slow stirring. The version is dense and not overly sweet. The shop also sells malunggay pesto, honey, and herbal teas. Walk-in customers welcome.</p>
<h2>Garden Cafe Tagbilaran</h2>
<p>Garden Cafe in Tagbilaran is the long-running restaurant run as a livelihood program for deaf staff. The menu includes a generous ube halaya plate and traditional Bohol breakfast dishes. The setting is calm, the service is communicated in a small printed menu and notes, and the kitchen is honest.</p>
<h2>Peanut Kisses</h2>
<p>Peanut kisses are bite-size peanut meringues from Dauis, packed in clear plastic bags of 50 to 100 pieces. The original maker, BFAD-licensed, has a small factory in Dauis and the product is sold at every pasalubong shop in Bohol. Crunchy outside, slightly chewy inside, with chopped peanuts in the meringue. The flavor is peanut-forward and the sweetness is balanced.</p>
<h2>Dauis Public Market</h2>
<p>The Dauis Public Market has stalls selling ube halaya by the bottle, peanut kisses by the bag, and other Bohol sweets like calamay (sticky rice in coconut shells). Try one stall, taste the ube halaya from a small spoon, then buy from the one you prefer. Prices are lower than the tourist shops.</p>
<h2>Calamay (Sticky Rice in Coconut Shell)</h2>
<p>Calamay is the Bohol kakanin made of glutinous rice flour, coconut milk, and brown sugar, cooked down to a thick caramel and poured into half-coconut shells. The result keeps for two weeks at room temperature. Buy two or three from the market for the boat ride home. Eat with a spoon, not by the bite.</p>
<h2>Cassava Pa-Hot Cakes</h2>
<p>Several Bohol bakeries sell hot cassava cake (made with grated cassava, coconut milk, eggs, and topped with cheese). The Bohol version is denser than the Manila supermarket cassava cake. Eat warm.</p>
<h2>The Pasalubong Stack</h2>
<p>Standard Bohol pasalubong bag: one bottle of ube halaya, two bags of peanut kisses, two calamay shells, one bag of broas, and one box of cassava cake. Total weight around two kilos. Survives the bus to the port and the boat back to Cebu without refrigeration.</p>
<h2>Heritage Side</h2>
<p>Pair the sweet trail with a stop at Baclayon Church (oldest stone church in the Philippines, 1727), Loboc Church, and Dauis Church. The heritage churches are calm and the sweet stops sit within driving distance of each.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Tagbilaran from Manila in one hour and 15 minutes. By ferry from Cebu, OceanJet to Tagbilaran takes two hours. From Tagbilaran, Panglao is a 20-minute drive across the bridge.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any month. The pasalubong shops run year-round. The third week of May is Sandugo Festival in Tagbilaran; the city is festive. Avoid Holy Week when many shops run short hours.</p>
<p>Bohol sweets are the pasalubong category most travelers underrate. A morning across the Tagbilaran and Dauis shops is enough to leave with the right bag.</p>
