    // 18. DAVAO DURIAN CRAWL
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/davao-durian-crawl',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Davao Durian Crawl: A First-Timer Guide',
        'slug' => 'davao-durian-crawl-first-timer-guide',
        'excerpt' => 'Davao is the durian capital of the Philippines. Here is a calm crawl through the fruit stalls, varieties, and the prepared durian sweets for the road.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Davao City grows around 80 percent of the country's durian and the city's relationship with the fruit shapes its food identity. The crawl below walks travelers through the varieties, the proper way to open and eat the fruit, and the prepared durian sweets that survive the trip home. First-timers welcome; the smell is real but the fruit is patient.</p>
<p>Durian season in Davao runs August to November with the peak in September and October. Off-season visits still find supply at the year-round vendors but the freshness drops. Tara, the kwento starts at Magsaysay Park.</p>
<h2>Magsaysay Park Durian Stalls</h2>
<p>Magsaysay Park has the durian stall row that defines the Davao tourist experience. Rows of vendors with piles of durian, machetes ready to open the fruit on demand. Tell the vendor your variety preference (Puyat, Arancillo, Native, D24, Monthong) and your budget. They will open it, set you up at a plastic table, and offer a wet wipe after.</p>
<h2>The Main Durian Varieties</h2>
<p>Puyat: large fruit, creamy flesh, mild sweetness. Beginner-friendly. Arancillo: smaller, more pungent, deeper flavor. Native: variable, often less consistent, lower price. D24 and Monthong: Thai varieties grown locally, milder than native Philippine cultivars. First-timers should try Puyat before working up to Arancillo.</p>
<h2>How to Eat Durian</h2>
<p>The vendor opens the fruit with a machete along the natural seams of the husk. The flesh sits in pods around the seeds. Pull a pod out with your fingers (use gloves if squeamish), eat the creamy flesh, spit the seed. Wipe your hands with the supplied wet wipe; the smell sticks to skin for hours.</p>
<h2>Durian Smell vs. Taste</h2>
<p>The smell is sulfurous and powerful. The taste is creamy, sweet, with notes of caramel, almond, and onion. The combination is unique. First bite is usually the test; the second and third bites usually convert the hesitant. Some people never convert. Both responses are normal.</p>
<h2>Durian Candy and Pastilles</h2>
<p>The Durian Garden, Lola Abon's, and several Davao bakeries sell durian candy: chewy durian-paste candies wrapped in cellophane. The candy is for people who like the flavor but cannot commit to a whole fresh fruit. Smell is reduced; flavor is concentrated.</p>
<h2>Durian Ice Cream</h2>
<p>The Davao stalls and many cafes serve durian ice cream. Cleaner than the fresh fruit, milder smell, sweeter flavor. Worth trying as a side step on the crawl.</p>
<h2>Durian Coffee and Pasalubong</h2>
<p>Buy durian candy, durian jam, and durian pastillas for pasalubong. Durian coffee blends are available at the airport. Fresh durian is banned from most hotels and from flights; do not try to carry it.</p>
<h2>Hotel Etiquette</h2>
<p>Most Davao hotels prohibit fresh durian in the rooms. Eat it at the park or at the durian-friendly cafes. Some restaurants have "durian smoking areas" for the fruit, which sounds odd until you appreciate the rule.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Davao from Manila in two hours. From Davao airport, a 20-minute taxi to Magsaysay Park.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>August to November is durian season with the peak in September to October. The Kadayawan Festival in August is the calendar high point for the fruit. Off-season visits still have durian but the variety thins and the prices rise.</p>
<p>Davao durian is a national category and Magsaysay Park is the easy entry point. A short crawl with a Puyat first and an Arancillo second is enough to know which side of the fruit you stand on.</p>
