    // 19. DAVAO TUNA MARKET
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/davao-tuna-market-dawn-run',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Davao Tuna Market: A Dawn Run for Travelers',
        'slug' => 'davao-tuna-market-dawn-run-travelers',
        'excerpt' => 'The Toril and Bankerohan fish markets in Davao see the morning catch from the Davao Gulf. Here is a calm dawn run for travelers who want to see the supply chain.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Davao Gulf is one of the productive tuna fishing grounds of the country and the morning catch lands at Toril Fish Port and Bankerohan Public Market before sunrise. Travelers who skip the dawn miss the chance to see how the fish moves from the boats to the auction tables to the restaurant plates by lunch. This is a calm dawn run with notes on what to look for and where to eat the fish after.</p>
<p>The run starts at 5 AM. Bring closed shoes, a light jacket, and a willingness to walk on wet floors. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Toril Fish Port</h2>
<p>Toril is the larger fish port in Davao city, about 30 minutes south of the city center. Boats unload between 4 and 6 AM. The catch is sorted on the wharf: tuna (yellowfin and skipjack), tanigue, lapu-lapu, marlin, and the smaller pelagic fish. The auction is fast and the prices move in shorthand.</p>
<h2>Bankerohan Public Market</h2>
<p>Bankerohan is the central public market of Davao and the closer option to most hotels. The fish section opens by 5 AM with the supply trucked from Toril and from smaller landing sites. The selection is wide and the price is wholesale until around 7 AM, then retail kicks in.</p>
<h2>What to Look For</h2>
<p>Eye clarity: clear, bright, slightly bulging. Gills: red, not brown. Scales: tight, not sloughing. Smell: clean sea, not ammonia. The fishmongers will hold up the fish for your inspection if you ask politely.</p>
<h2>Kinilaw on the Gulf</h2>
<p>Kinilaw is the Mindanao fish ceviche: raw fish (usually tanigue, mackerel, or tuna) cured in vinegar, calamansi, ginger, onion, and chili. The dish is at its sharpest with fish caught hours earlier. Several Davao restaurants pick up fish at the morning market and serve kinilaw at lunch. Lachi's Sans Rival, Marina Tuna, and Tiny Kitchen are the calm sit-downs.</p>
<h2>Tuna Belly and Tuna Panga</h2>
<p>Tuna belly (the fatty cut) is the prized portion of yellowfin tuna and Davao restaurants serve it grilled or fried. Tuna panga (jaw collar) is the meaty bone-and-flesh cut grilled over coals; eat with your hands. Both are Davao-Gensan classics and worth the dinner stop.</p>
<h2>The General Santos Connection</h2>
<p>General Santos (GenSan) is the bigger tuna port in the region, 3 hours from Davao. Davao gets a portion of GenSan supply and GenSan handles the export-grade tuna. The Davao market scene is the smaller, more accessible version of the GenSan dawn fish run.</p>
<h2>Eating Plan After the Market</h2>
<p>Standard plan: market by 5 AM, breakfast at Bankerohan or Toril carinderias by 7 AM (rice, fried fish, coffee), nap from 9 to 11, lunch of kinilaw and tuna belly at noon. The full circle.</p>
<h2>What to Bring Home</h2>
<p>Vacuum-packed tuna belly and dried fish travel home from Davao airport. Buy at the airport pasalubong shop rather than the market unless you have a chiller and a confirmed flight. The customs and freshness logistics are easier post-security.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Davao from Manila in two hours. From Davao city, taxi or Grab to Bankerohan is 10 minutes; Toril is 30 to 40 minutes south.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any morning. Weekdays are calmer. The August Kadayawan Festival is high tourist season; the market still runs. Avoid Holy Week if you want a calm dawn; the supply schedule shifts.</p>
<p>The Davao dawn fish market is the easy supply-chain education for travelers who eat seafood. Two hours at the market and a noon kinilaw lunch closes the loop.</p>
