    // 20. VIGAN EMPANADA
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/vigan-empanada-makers',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Vigan Empanada Trail: Three Stalls, One Orange Pastry',
        'slug' => 'vigan-empanada-trail-three-stalls',
        'excerpt' => 'Vigan empanada is the orange-shelled, longganisa-stuffed snack of Ilocos Sur. Here is a calm trail through three stalls that define the local version.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Vigan empanada is the bright orange-shelled, longganisa-stuffed, papaya-filled, egg-cracked snack that travelers eat standing up at Plaza Burgos in Ilocos Sur. The pastry is rice flour with annatto (the orange color), the filling is Vigan longganisa, grated papaya, mung bean sprouts, and a whole egg cracked in just before frying. This is a calm trail through three of the Plaza Burgos stalls that define the local empanada.</p>
<p>The trail is a 90-minute eat-around in central Vigan, paired with a Calle Crisologo evening walk. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Plaza Burgos</h2>
<p>Plaza Burgos is the open plaza in front of Vigan Cathedral and the empanada stalls line the side facing the cathedral. Five to seven stalls operate. Each has a queue at peak hours (5 to 8 PM and 11 AM to 2 PM). Tell the cook your order: regular (with egg), special (with more longganisa), or jumbo (all the above with extra filling). The cook fills, folds, fries, and hands the empanada in a paper bag.</p>
<h2>Irene's Empanada</h2>
<p>Irene's is one of the named stalls and has been operating for decades. The shell here is the orange-orange color (high annatto) and the longganisa is cut into larger pieces. The egg is fully cooked. Vinegar dip is on the table. Eat standing up or at the plaza benches.</p>
<h2>Cita's Empanada</h2>
<p>Cita's runs a smaller stall and the shell is slightly thinner. The longganisa here is finely chopped and the egg yolk is just set, slightly runny. The vinegar is spicier. Cita's is the foodie favorite of the row.</p>
<h2>Sariwa Empanada</h2>
<p>Sariwa keeps the empanada fresher (sariwa means fresh) by frying smaller batches. The shell holds the crunch longer. Worth ordering as the third stall on the comparison run.</p>
<h2>Comparing Three</h2>
<p>Three empanadas in 90 minutes is the standard trail. Order one regular at each stall. Eat over three sittings on the plaza benches. The variations are subtle but visible: shell crunch, egg done-ness, longganisa-to-papaya ratio, and vinegar heat. Bring water and a willingness to share half with a friend.</p>
<h2>Royal Bibingka Side Stop</h2>
<p>Between empanadas, walk one block to a Royal Bibingka shop. Vigan bibingka is denser and yellower than the Manila version; the Royal brand is the easy commercial stop. Pair with a small cup of coffee.</p>
<h2>Vigan Longganisa Standalone</h2>
<p>If the empanada is your introduction to Vigan longganisa, follow up with a longganisa breakfast plate at any of the Calle Crisologo restaurants. The longganisa here is garlicky and vinegary, shorter than Lucban, and pairs with rice and a fried egg.</p>
<h2>Pair with Calle Crisologo</h2>
<p>End the trail with a calesa ride or a slow walk down Calle Crisologo at sunset. The cobblestone street with the heritage houses lights up around 6 PM. The empanada stalls are a five-minute walk from one end of the street.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Laoag from Manila in one hour 15 minutes, then van to Vigan (one hour 30 minutes). By bus from Cubao, the trip is 8 to 9 hours overnight to Vigan terminal.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any month except Holy Week. The first week of May is the Viva Vigan Festival and the empanada stalls expand. December cool weather is the friendliest for the standing-up eating. Weekday evenings have the calmest queues.</p>
<p>Vigan empanada is the regional snack that defines the after-dark Calle Crisologo experience. Three stalls in a row is the easy way to taste the variations on a single afternoon.</p>
