    // 21. BURNAYAN POTTERY VIGAN
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/vigan-burnayan-pottery-deep-dive',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Burnayan Pottery in Vigan: A Heritage Craft Deep-Dive',
        'slug' => 'burnayan-pottery-vigan-heritage-craft',
        'excerpt' => 'The Pagburnayan jar factories in Vigan still throw clay on foot-pedal wheels. Here is a calm visit and the kwento behind the four-century-old pottery tradition.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Burnay jars are the dark earthenware vessels Vigan has been producing for over four centuries. Used for storing bagoong (fish paste), basi (sugarcane wine), and vinegar, the jars are made of local clay mixed with fine sand, thrown on a foot-pedal wheel, and fired in a brick kiln fueled by rice husks. The technique came with Chinese potters in the colonial era and the craft survives in two or three working pagburnayan workshops in Vigan. This is a calm visit and a kwento of the craft.</p>
<p>The pagburnayan workshops are on the northern side of Vigan, a 10-minute calesa ride from Calle Crisologo. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Pagburnayan ni Ruby (RG Jar Factory)</h2>
<p>RG Jar Factory in Pagburnayan area is the visitor-friendly workshop on the standard heritage circuit. The grounds include the kiln, the clay mixing pit, the wheel area, and a small showroom. Visitors can watch the wheel-throwing demo and try their hand at the wheel for a small fee.</p>
<h2>How the Jars Are Made</h2>
<p>Step one: clay is mixed with fine sand in the pit by a carabao walking in circles for hours. Step two: the wet clay is shaped on a wheel pedaled by foot, hands on the clay, water dripping. Step three: the wet jar is air-dried for days. Step four: the jar is loaded into the brick kiln. Step five: rice husks are loaded around and inside the jars, set on fire, and burned at low temperature for three days. Step six: the jars are cooled and pulled.</p>
<h2>The Carabao Pit</h2>
<p>The carabao mixing the clay is the most-photographed part of the visit. The animal walks slow circles in a deep pit of wet clay, kneading the material with hoof and weight. The pit is older than electricity in Vigan. Ask permission before photos; the carabao is a working animal, not a prop.</p>
<h2>Wheel Throwing Demo</h2>
<p>The master potter sits on a short bench at the wheel, pedals with one foot, and pulls a kilo of clay into a tall jar in about three minutes. The wheel is unpowered; only the potter's foot and the wet clay touch it. Watching the form rise is calmer than expected; the rhythm is slow and steady.</p>
<h2>The Kiln</h2>
<p>The brick kiln is the dome-shaped structure with a wide opening. Up to 200 jars are loaded for a single firing. Rice husks burn slow and at a temperature low enough to not crack the jars. The kiln stays warm for three days. Locals say the secret to Vigan burnay is the husk firing.</p>
<h2>What You Can Buy</h2>
<p>Small burnay jars (palayok size) for kitchen use or as souvenirs are available at the workshop showrooms. Larger jars for bagoong storage are sold by the kilo of clay used. The smallest pieces fit in carry-on luggage; the medium and large jars need shipping.</p>
<h2>Other Vigan Heritage Stops</h2>
<p>Pair the pagburnayan visit with Calle Crisologo, Vigan Cathedral, Crisologo Museum, and the Bantay Bell Tower. A full heritage day covers all of them with calesa rides between stops.</p>
<h2>Why It Matters</h2>
<p>Burnay jars are the everyday vessels that hold fermented Ilocos cuisine: bagoong, basi, suka, and patis. Without the jars, the Ilocos food culture loses a layer of its storage chain. The craft survives because the food survives.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Pagburnayan is in Brgy. Pagburnayan, Vigan. Take a calesa, tricycle, or short walk from Plaza Salcedo. Open most days; ask the calesa driver for the current visiting hours.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Any month. Weekday mornings are the calmest. Avoid Holy Week and the Viva Vigan Festival week if you want a quiet workshop visit.</p>
<p>Burnayan is the slow heritage stop that travelers add to the Vigan walk and remember the longest. A morning at the wheel teaches more about Ilocos food culture than any restaurant menu.</p>
