    // 22. TAAL HERITAGE TOWN
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/taal-heritage-town-walk',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Taal Heritage Town Walk in Batangas',
        'slug' => 'taal-heritage-town-walk-batangas',
        'excerpt' => 'Taal town in Batangas has the largest ensemble of Spanish-era heritage houses in Luzon. Here is a calm walking guide.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Taal is the small town in Batangas with the largest concentration of Spanish-era heritage houses in Luzon. The town center is built around the Basilica of Saint Martin of Tours, the largest Catholic church in Asia by floor area, and the cobblestone streets around the basilica are lined with bahay na bato houses still owned by the original families. This is a calm walking guide for a half-day Taal visit.</p>
<p>Taal town is around two hours from Manila via STAR Tollway and a different town from Taal Volcano in Tagaytay. Tara, the kwento starts at the basilica.</p>
<h2>Basilica of Saint Martin of Tours</h2>
<p>The Basilica is the largest church in Asia by floor area, finished in 1878. The facade is white stone with twin bell towers and a grand portico. Inside, the nave is wide and the side chapels hold santos carved in the heritage style. Free entry; modest dress. Climb the bell tower if access is open for the view of Taal town.</p>
<h2>Plaza Mariano Diokno</h2>
<p>The plaza in front of the basilica is the center of the town and the reference point for the heritage walk. The streets radiating from the plaza hold the heritage houses, most still privately owned, some converted to museum-style visits.</p>
<h2>Casa Villavicencio (Wedding Gift House)</h2>
<p>Casa Villavicencio, the so-called "wedding gift house," was built in 1850 by Eulalio Villavicencio for his wife Gliceria Marella, a leading supporter of the Philippine Revolution. The house is open to visitors with a small entrance fee. The interior preserves the period furniture, the family portraits, and the chapel where Gliceria reportedly sewed flags for the Katipunan.</p>
<h2>Casa Marcela Mariño Agoncillo</h2>
<p>Casa Marcela Agoncillo is the house of the woman who sewed the first Philippine flag in 1898 in Hong Kong. The house has been converted to a museum with the family's belongings, a replica of the flag, and notes on the Agoncillo family. Free entry on most days.</p>
<h2>Apolinario Mabini Shrine</h2>
<p>Mabini, the "sublime paralytic" and brains of the Philippine Revolution, is from neighboring Tanauan but a small Mabini shrine in Taal honors his role in the area. Worth a 20-minute stop.</p>
<h2>Taal Public Market and Tapang Taal</h2>
<p>The Taal Public Market on weekends has the embroidery row (Taal is the embroidery capital of the country), the taal tapang counters (pork tapa with garlic and vinegar), and the longganisa Taal stalls. Buy a kilo of tapang Taal and a half kilo of Taal longganisa for the road.</p>
<h2>Embroidery and Barong Tagalog</h2>
<p>Taal makes the country's finest hand-embroidered piña fabrics for barong tagalog. The embroidery shops along Calle MH del Pilar carry finished barongs and custom orders. A finished barong in piña silk takes weeks to a month to produce; the embroidery is intricate and family-passed.</p>
<h2>Cafe Hotel of Lima or Sentro 1771 (For Lunch)</h2>
<p>The lunch options in Taal are humble: carinderias around the plaza, a few cafes in the heritage houses, and the Hotel of Lima (an old casa converted to a guesthouse with a cafe). Order tapang Taal, Taal longganisa, and adobo sa dilaw (yellow adobo with turmeric).</p>
<h2>Pair with Other Stops</h2>
<p>Taal pairs well with Las Casas-style heritage day plans. Combine with Lipa for the coffee morning, Tagaytay for the view, or Calatagan for the beach.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Drive from Manila via SLEX, STAR Tollway, Lemery exit, then Taal town (around 2 hours). By bus, take a Lemery or Lipa bus from Buendia and ask to be dropped at Taal town.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Weekday mornings are the calmest. The third week of December is the town fiesta; the heritage walk is festive but loud. December cool weather is the friendliest for the walking.</p>
<p>Taal is the heritage walk that travelers should do at least once. The basilica, the casa houses, and the embroidery row together make the best ensemble of Spanish-era Batangas.</p>
