    // 24. CALLE REAL ILOILO DEEP DIVE
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/calle-real-iloilo-heritage-deep-dive',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Calle Real Iloilo: A Heritage Architecture Deep-Dive',
        'slug' => 'calle-real-iloilo-heritage-architecture-deep-dive',
        'excerpt' => 'Calle Real in Iloilo City has the densest run of American-era commercial buildings in the country. Here is a slow walking guide.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Calle Real, officially J.M. Basa Street, is the heritage commercial corridor of Iloilo City and one of the densest stretches of American-era and late Spanish-era buildings in the country. The street served as the financial center of Iloilo during the sugar boom of the early 1900s, and the buildings still standing trace the architectural moves from Beaux-Arts to Art Deco to American commercial vernacular. This is a slow walking guide.</p>
<p>Calle Real is in central Iloilo City, walkable from the Plaza Libertad and the cathedral. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Plaza Libertad as Starting Point</h2>
<p>Plaza Libertad is the plaza where the Philippine flag was first raised in the Visayas in 1898. The plaza is calm during the day and a good orientation point. The Iloilo Cathedral (Jaro Cathedral is in a different district; the central church here is the San Jose de Placer Parish) and the surrounding heritage row anchor the walking circuit.</p>
<h2>International Hotel Building (Daza Building)</h2>
<p>The Daza Building, also known as the International Hotel, is one of the most ornate buildings on Calle Real. Beaux-Arts facade with detailed plasterwork. The hotel has been restored and now operates as a boutique heritage hotel with a cafe on the ground floor.</p>
<h2>YMCA Building and Lopez Heritage Building</h2>
<p>The YMCA Building dates to the 1920s and the Lopez Building is one of the early commercial high-rises in the Visayas. Both have been restored. The Lopez Building houses a museum-cafe on the ground floor.</p>
<h2>Streetscape Details</h2>
<p>Look up. The cornices, the moldings, and the original signage hints (some buildings still have ghost lettering of original tenants) tell the story of the street. The arcades along the building fronts shaded shoppers from the sun and the rain; the practice is older than air conditioning and works better.</p>
<h2>Customs House (Aduana)</h2>
<p>The Customs House at the end of Calle Real, near the port, is one of the older Spanish-era buildings on the corridor. The thick walls and the colonnaded facade survived earthquakes and World War II. Now a working customs office; exterior viewing only.</p>
<h2>Streamlined Modern and Art Deco</h2>
<p>Iloilo had a small Art Deco movement in the 1930s and several Calle Real buildings show streamlined modern facades. The Eagle Theater, the Roxas Building, and a few smaller commercial spaces date to this period.</p>
<h2>Iloilo Cathedral (Jaro)</h2>
<p>Take a 15-minute Grab ride to Jaro Cathedral for the second half of the heritage walk. The Jaro Cathedral has its bell tower across the street (rare for Philippine churches) and the Jaro Plaza heritage houses are worth a slow afternoon.</p>
<h2>Cafe Stops</h2>
<p>Madge Cafe in La Paz, Camina Balay nga Bato in Arevalo, and the Lopez Building cafe are the calm coffee stops on the heritage route. Pair with biscocho or pancit Molo.</p>
<h2>The Bigger Iloilo Heritage Loop</h2>
<p>Calle Real, Jaro Cathedral, Molo Church, Mansion Molo, La Paz Public Market, and Camina Balay nga Bato make a full heritage day in Iloilo. Two days does the wider circuit at a calm pace.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Iloilo from Manila in one hour 15 minutes. Calle Real is 20 minutes by Grab from the airport. Walking from any central Iloilo hotel.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Weekday mornings are the calmest. The fourth week of January is Dinagyang Festival; the city is loud. December cool weather is the friendliest for the slow walk.</p>
<p>Calle Real is the architectural history lesson disguised as a slow morning walk. An hour and a coffee stop is enough; the buildings will hold their kwento.</p>
