    // 25. SARIAYA CASA WALK
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/sariaya-casa-walk-quezon',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Sariaya Casa Walk: A Quezon Heritage Day',
        'slug' => 'sariaya-casa-walk-quezon-heritage-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Sariaya in Quezon Province has the cleanest run of Art Deco heritage houses outside Manila. Here is a calm half-day walking guide.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Sariaya, Quezon is the small town between Lucena and the Sariaya-Tayabas border with the cleanest concentration of Art Deco heritage houses outside Metro Manila. The houses were built in the 1930s by sugar and coconut barons in the late-American-era style; the streets they line have survived with modest changes. This is a calm half-day walking guide for travelers passing through Quezon.</p>
<p>Sariaya is two and a half hours from Manila via SLEX. The walk pairs well with a Lucban kakanin morning or a Tayabas heritage stop. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Plaza Sariaya</h2>
<p>The plaza in front of the Sariaya Church anchors the walking circuit. The church is a stone parish from the 1700s with a wide bell tower. Free entry. Modest dress. The streets radiating from the plaza hold the heritage houses.</p>
<h2>Casa de Comunidad de Sariaya</h2>
<p>The Casa de Comunidad is the town's heritage and cultural center, housed in a restored ancestral home. The casa runs exhibits on Sariaya history, hosts community events, and offers walking-tour briefings. A 30-minute visit before the heritage walk is useful for context.</p>
<h2>Natalio Enriquez Ancestral House</h2>
<p>The Natalio Enriquez house is the most-photographed of the Sariaya heritage homes. Built in the late 1930s in Art Deco style, the facade has the cleaner geometric lines of the period. Privately owned; exterior viewing only, occasional public tours on weekends.</p>
<h2>Rodriguez Ancestral House (Villa Sariaya)</h2>
<p>The Rodriguez Ancestral House is one of the larger heritage homes and is sometimes open for tours by appointment. The interior preserves period furniture, antique mirrors, and family photographs.</p>
<h2>Gala Rodriguez Mansion</h2>
<p>The Gala Mansion is the third on the standard tour. Pink facade, deep silong, and a wide carriageway. Currently a private residence; exterior viewing.</p>
<h2>Casa de Comunidad Annex</h2>
<p>The annex behind the main casa runs as a small cafe and gift shop. Order Sariaya merienda plates, kakanin, and coffee.</p>
<h2>Sariaya Cuisine</h2>
<p>Sariaya is part of the Quezon kakanin and longganisa belt. Pair the heritage walk with broas, longganisa Sariaya, and pancit chami. The longganisa here is sweeter than Lucban and shorter. The pancit chami is a Quezon noodle dish with miki, lechon kawali, and vegetables.</p>
<h2>Agos sa Lansangan Festival</h2>
<p>The third week of May is the Agos sa Lansangan (Flow Through the Streets) Festival, Sariaya's local version of Pahiyas with elaborate house facades. If you can time the trip, the festival adds a layer of color to the heritage walk. The festival is calmer than Lucban Pahiyas and the houses are larger.</p>
<h2>Pair with Lucban or Tayabas</h2>
<p>Sariaya is 30 minutes from Lucban and 15 minutes from Tayabas. A two-stop heritage day with Sariaya in the morning and Lucban or Tayabas in the afternoon works comfortably.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Bus from Manila to Lucena (three hours), then jeepney to Sariaya (15 minutes). By car, SLEX exit at Sto. Tomas, then south on the Maharlika Highway through Tiaong and Candelaria to Sariaya.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Weekday mornings are the calmest. The third week of May is Agos sa Lansangan; the streets are festive. December cool weather is the friendliest for the slow walk.</p>
<p>Sariaya is the heritage walk most Quezon travelers race past on their way to Lucban. A morning slowed down on Calle Mabini and Calle Rizal teaches a different lesson about Tagalog provincial architecture.</p>
