    // 27. CAVITE REVOLUTIONARY CHURCHES
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/cavite-revolutionary-churches-loop',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Cavite Revolutionary Churches Loop',
        'slug' => 'cavite-revolutionary-churches-loop',
        'excerpt' => 'Cavite holds the parish churches tied to the Philippine Revolution of 1896. Here is a calm one-day loop through the most-photographed of them.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cavite was the cradle of the Philippine Revolution in 1896 and the parish churches in the province carry the memory of those years. The Aguinaldo Shrine in Kawit, the Imus Cathedral, the Maragondon Church, and the Naic Church each tie to a specific moment in the revolution. This is a calm one-day loop for travelers interested in revolutionary heritage.</p>
<p>The loop is a one-car day from Manila, around 80 km of driving across Cavite. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Aguinaldo Shrine (Kawit)</h2>
<p>Aguinaldo Shrine is the ancestral home of Emilio Aguinaldo, the first President of the Philippines, in Kawit, Cavite. The Philippine independence was proclaimed from the balcony of this house on June 12, 1898. The shrine is now a museum with the original furniture, secret passages, and family memorabilia. Free entry. Closed Mondays. Allow 90 minutes.</p>
<h2>Imus Cathedral</h2>
<p>The Imus Cathedral, Nuestra Señora del Pilar Parish, is the seat of the Diocese of Imus and the site of the Battle of Imus in 1896, an early Filipino victory in the revolution. The current cathedral is the rebuilt version of the parish that was damaged during the war. Free entry; modest dress.</p>
<h2>Bonifacio Trial House (Maragondon)</h2>
<p>The Bonifacio Trial House in Maragondon is where Andres Bonifacio was tried in 1897 in the Tejeros faction split of the revolution. The house has been preserved with exhibits on the trial and the disputed verdict. Maragondon Church is adjacent and worth a 20-minute stop. The drive from Kawit takes around 90 minutes.</p>
<h2>Naic Church</h2>
<p>Naic Church and the adjacent Naic Convent are tied to the early consolidation of the revolution under Aguinaldo. The convent housed the revolutionary leaders briefly in 1897. The church is a stone parish with a simple facade.</p>
<h2>Tejeros Convention Site (San Francisco de Malabon, now General Trias)</h2>
<p>The Tejeros Convention site in General Trias is where the disputed 1897 election of revolutionary officers took place. The convention split the Katipunan and led to the Bonifacio trial. A small marker and a chapel remain.</p>
<h2>Battle of Binakayan-Dalahican (Kawit)</h2>
<p>The Battle of Binakayan-Dalahican in 1896 is one of the early Filipino tactical victories in the revolution. A small marker and a battlefield park in Kawit commemorate the event. Worth a 30-minute stop after the Aguinaldo Shrine.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat in Cavite</h2>
<p>Lunch options: kakanin and bibingka stalls in Kawit, Tagalog plates in Imus, and the seaside carinderias in Maragondon. The Tagalog Cavite cuisine leans on pancit pusit (squid noodles), suman, sapin-sapin, and longanisang Imus. Try one stall in each town.</p>
<h2>Bonifacio and Aguinaldo Reading</h2>
<p>The two figures defined the Philippine Revolution and their political conflict shaped the trajectory of the war and the republic. Reading a short biography of each before the loop deepens the visit. The shrines do not always present both sides equally; the Bonifacio Trial House is the more conflicted stop.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Drive from Manila via Coastal Road and CAVITEX to Kawit. The loop continues through Imus, then south to Naic and Maragondon. The return to Manila via the Aguinaldo Highway or CAVITEX.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>June 12 (Independence Day) is the calendar peak at Aguinaldo Shrine; the rest of the year is calmer. Weekday mornings are the friendliest. November 30 (Bonifacio Day) draws crowds to the Maragondon and Tejeros sites.</p>
<p>The Cavite revolutionary loop is the heritage day that turns abstract history into walked-through buildings. A morning of the Aguinaldo balcony and an afternoon of the Bonifacio trial house leaves with both sides of the kwento.</p>
