    // 30. MASSKARA DEEP DIVE
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/masskara-bacolod-deep-dive',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Masskara Festival: A Bacolod Deep-Dive',
        'slug' => 'masskara-bacolod-festival-deep-dive',
        'excerpt' => 'Masskara fills Bacolod with smiling masks every October. Here is a calm deep-dive on the origin, the parade, and the chicken inasal that comes with it.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Masskara is the Bacolod festival every fourth week of October celebrating the smiling masks the city built into its civic identity. The festival started in 1980 as a community response to the sugar industry crash and the Don Juan ferry tragedy. The smiling masks were chosen to mark Bacolod as the "City of Smiles" through the hardship. The festival has grown into a month-long celebration with parades, street parties, food fairs, and a sustained spirit of joyful resistance. This is a deep-dive.</p>
<p>Masskara is in October, with the highlight weekend on the fourth Saturday and Sunday. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Origin Story</h2>
<p>The festival was born from twin tragedies in 1980. The sugar industry, the backbone of Negros Occidental, collapsed when global sugar prices crashed. In the same year, the Don Juan ferry collided with a tanker off the Negros coast, killing many Negrenses including children of prominent families. The community leaders decided to respond with masks and dancing rather than mourning, choosing joy as resistance. The festival has retained that origin meaning.</p>
<h2>The Masks</h2>
<p>The Masskara masks are colorful, smiling, often plumed and beaded. Schools, barangays, and corporate sponsors enter contingents with elaborate mask designs. The masks cover the dancers' faces during the parade; the dance is the focus, the individual identity is not.</p>
<h2>The Street Dance Competition</h2>
<p>The street dance competition on the fourth Saturday is the parade highlight. Contingents from across Negros and the country dance choreographed routines along the parade route. The masks, costumes, and choreography are judged.</p>
<h2>Electric Masskara</h2>
<p>Electric Masskara is the evening version of the festival with lighted masks and dancing under stage lights. The setting is at the Bacolod Public Plaza and Lacson Street. The energy is the street-party side of the festival.</p>
<h2>Chicken Inasal at Manokan Country</h2>
<p>Pair the festival with chicken inasal at Manokan Country, the row of grilled chicken restaurants in Bacolod. Order paa, pecho, or atay isaw with garlic rice and chicken oil. Pair with vinegar dip and soft drinks. The standard order for two people is two chicken pieces, two rice, and a soft drink.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Book Bacolod hotels three to six months ahead for Masskara weekend. Lacson Street hotels are closest to the parade. Silay (30 minutes north) is a calmer alternative if you have a car.</p>
<h2>Crowd Notes</h2>
<p>The parade route fills by mid-morning. Bring water, a hat, and comfortable shoes. Travel light. The Lacson Street strip is the social hub in the evenings.</p>
<h2>Pair with Silay or Don Salvador Benedicto</h2>
<p>The Silay heritage walk and the Don Salvador Benedicto cool-weather climate are within driving distance and pair well with Masskara week if you want days outside the festival energy.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Bacolod-Silay International Airport from Manila in one hour 15 minutes. The airport is in Silay, 30 minutes from Bacolod city.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Fourth week of October every year. The festival highlight is the fourth Saturday and Sunday. The full month of October has Masskara-related events building up to the highlight.</p>
<p>Masskara is the festival that earned its identity through resistance and joy. A weekend in Bacolod with the parade and the chicken inasal is the calmest way to feel both sides of the kwento.</p>
