    // 31. ATI-ATIHAN
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/ati-atihan-kalibo-deep-dive',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Ati-Atihan in Kalibo: A January Festival Deep-Dive',
        'slug' => 'ati-atihan-kalibo-january-festival',
        'excerpt' => 'Ati-Atihan in Kalibo is the original "Mother of Philippine Festivals." Here is a calm deep-dive on the soot, the Santo Niño, and the parade days.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Ati-Atihan in Kalibo, Aklan, is one of the oldest Philippine festivals and locally called the Mother of all Philippine Festivals. The celebration honors the Santo Niño with the parade tradition that dates to the 13th-century arrival of Bornean datus in Panay and the gift of land from the local Ati people. Today, revelers paint themselves with soot, dress in tribal costumes, and dance in the streets for a week in January. This is a calm deep-dive.</p>
<p>Ati-Atihan runs the second and third weeks of January with the highlight on the third Sunday. The Sinulog in Cebu runs at the same time so travelers usually choose one. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Origin Story</h2>
<p>The legend traces the festival to the 13th century, when 10 Bornean datus arrived in Panay fleeing their home and bought lowland from the local Ati people (Negrito tribe). To celebrate the friendship, both groups blackened their faces with soot. When Spanish missionaries later introduced the Santo Niño, the tradition merged into a Christian festival. The "Ati-Atihan" means "to be like Ati."</p>
<h2>The Soot Painting</h2>
<p>Travelers and locals paint their faces and bodies with soot as a tribute to the Ati people. The soot is real charcoal-based; bring a change of clothes you do not mind getting dirty. Most revelers paint in the morning and wash in the afternoon.</p>
<h2>"Hala Bira"</h2>
<p>"Hala Bira, Puera Pasma" is the Ati-Atihan chant, roughly meaning "go for it, no excuses." The chant runs through the parades, the bars, and the street parties.</p>
<h2>The Tribu Contingents</h2>
<p>The Ati-Atihan parade is structured around tribus (tribes), groups of dancers from different parts of Aklan and beyond. Each tribu has its own costume, choreography, and rhythm section (drums and bamboo instruments). The judging is on the final Sunday.</p>
<h2>The Santo Niño Procession</h2>
<p>The religious anchor of the festival is the Santo Niño procession on the Saturday before the final Sunday. The image is carried through Kalibo with prayers and singing.</p>
<h2>The Parade Days</h2>
<p>The festival builds through the week: tribu rehearsals on weekdays, novena masses each evening, fluvial procession on a designated day, and the grand parade on the third Sunday. The energy peaks Saturday night and Sunday afternoon.</p>
<h2>Food at Ati-Atihan</h2>
<p>Aklan food traditions show up in the festival: pancit Kalibo, binakol (chicken soup in coconut), and chicharon kalibo. Boracay is one hour north; many travelers split their week between Boracay quiet days and Kalibo festival days.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Book Kalibo accommodation three to six months ahead. The parade route hotels go first. Boracay is a calm alternative with daily transfers.</p>
<h2>Crowd Notes</h2>
<p>Wear clothes you do not mind staining with soot. Bring water, a bandana for the dust, and comfortable shoes. Cash is the standard for street food and tribu donation boxes.</p>
<h2>Pair with Boracay</h2>
<p>Most Ati-Atihan travelers fly into Kalibo airport and split the week between the festival and Boracay. The combo works because Ati-Atihan is loud and Boracay is calm.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Kalibo from Manila in one hour. The Kalibo airport is the main entry. Boracay is a 90-minute van and boat ride from Kalibo.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Second and third weeks of January. The final Sunday is the highlight. Booking ahead is necessary.</p>
<p>Ati-Atihan is the oldest of the Philippine festivals and the one with the deepest origin story. A weekend in Kalibo with soot on your hands and Hala Bira on your tongue is the calmest way to feel the tradition.</p>
