        'excerpt' => 'Panagbenga is the Baguio flower festival every February. Here is a calm deep-dive on the parade, the cool weather, and the crowd plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Panagbenga is the Baguio flower festival every February, a month-long celebration of the cool-weather flowers that grow in the Cordillera highlands. The festival was started in 1996 as a community response to the 1990 Luzon earthquake and the recovery of Baguio. The grand parade on the last Sunday of February features flower-decorated floats, street dancers in flower costumes, and the Session Road street fair. This is a calm deep-dive.</p>
<p>Panagbenga runs the full month of February with the highlight on the final weekend. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Origin Story</h2>
<p>Panagbenga (Kankanaey for "season of blooming") was created in 1996 by a tourism committee to revive Baguio after the 1990 earthquake that damaged the city. The festival succeeded; it became one of the most-attended Philippine festivals and now defines Baguio's February calendar.</p>
<h2>The Grand Parade</h2>
<p>The grand street dance parade is on the last Saturday of February. Schools and barangays from Baguio and Benguet enter contingents in flower-themed costumes and choreography. The route runs from Athletic Bowl down Session Road.</p>
<h2>The Float Parade</h2>
<p>The float parade is on the last Sunday of February. Flower-covered floats from corporate sponsors and Cordillera flower farms make the slow procession through downtown Baguio. The floats are built over weeks and the flower work is the headline draw.</p>
<h2>Session Road Closed to Vehicles</h2>
<p>After the float parade, Session Road becomes a street fair for the remaining days of February. Food stalls, craft vendors, and street performers take over the road. The fair is the calmer post-parade entry point into Panagbenga.</p>
<h2>Burnham Park Flower Show</h2>
<p>The Burnham Park flower show runs alongside the festival. Greenhouses and farms display flower arrangements; the lake is decorated for the occasion. Free entry to the park.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Book Baguio accommodation three to six months ahead. The hotels near Session Road and Burnham Park fill first. Tagaytay-style cottages and inns at the city outskirts work for travelers with cars.</p>
<h2>Crowd Notes</h2>
<p>The parade weekends are the densest. Wear layers (Baguio mornings can drop below 15 degrees Celsius), comfortable shoes, and bring water. The Session Road street fair runs for over a week post-parade and is the calmer way to experience the festival.</p>
<h2>Pair with Local Stops</h2>
<p>Baguio in February is at its coolest. Pair Panagbenga with Mines View, La Trinidad strawberry farm, Camp John Hay, and the Tam-Awan Village. Two to three days covers the festival highlights and the city.</p>
<h2>Cool Weather Food</h2>
<p>Baguio food in February: strawberry shortcake from Good Shepherd or Vizco's, brewed coffee at any Session Road cafe, pinikpikan at the Tam-Awan Village restaurant, and the Baguio Public Market produce. The cool weather pairs naturally with the coffee.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Bus from Cubao or Pasay to Baguio takes 4 to 6 hours via TPLEX and SCTEX. Victory Liner and Genesis run multiple daily trips. By car, NLEX to TPLEX to Marcos Highway.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The full month of February. The final weekend (last Saturday and Sunday) is the parade highlight. The first three weeks are calmer with the buildup events.</p>
<p>Panagbenga is the festival that revived a damaged city and grew into a national draw. A weekend in Baguio with flowers in your peripheral vision is the calmest way to enjoy the cool-weather February.</p>
