    // 37. APALIT SUKAD
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatseralovers.com/apalit-sukad-festival-pampanga',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsera Lovers',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Apung Iru and Apalit Sukad: A Pampanga River Festival',
        'slug' => 'apung-iru-apalit-sukad-pampanga-river-festival',
        'excerpt' => 'Apalit in Pampanga celebrates Apung Iru with a fluvial procession on the Pampanga River every June 28 to 30. Here is a calm festival note.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Apalit, Pampanga, holds the Apung Iru Festival every June 28 to 30 to honor San Pedro Apostol, the patron saint of the town. The highlight is the fluvial procession on the Pampanga River with the image of Apung Iru on a decorated pagoda boat. The festival combines river-village tradition with a quiet Kapampangan town fiesta atmosphere. This is a calm note for travelers.</p>
<p>Apalit is around 90 minutes from Manila via NLEX. The festival pairs well with a Pampanga food trail on calmer days. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Image of Apung Iru</h2>
<p>"Apung Iru" is Kapampangan for "Old Pedro" or "Grandfather Pedro." The image of San Pedro Apostol enshrined at the Apalit Parish Church has been venerated by the river-village community for centuries. The image is sacred to local fishermen; the river-procession tradition predates official tourism.</p>
<h2>The Fluvial Procession</h2>
<p>The procession on June 28 carries the image on a decorated pagoda-style boat down the Pampanga River. Hundreds of supporting boats join. The procession is loud, festive, and family-attended. Watch from the river bank or join a friend's boat if you have a Apalit connection.</p>
<h2>Apalit Parish Church</h2>
<p>The parish church of San Pedro Apostol in Apalit town is the religious center. The image is enshrined here outside festival days. Free entry; modest dress.</p>
<h2>The Pampanga River</h2>
<p>The Pampanga River runs through Apalit and other lowland Pampanga towns. The river has been the commercial and cultural artery of the area for centuries. The fluvial procession is the festival expression of the river's importance.</p>
<h2>Kapampangan Food at the Festival</h2>
<p>The festival days fill the Apalit plaza with food stalls: sisig, pancit luglug, kakanin, and the local Apalit specialty of pindang damulag (carabao tapa). Try the pindang as the local plate of the trip.</p>
<h2>Pindang Damulag</h2>
<p>Pindang damulag is dried, salted carabao meat, fried and served with garlic rice and vinegar dip. The flavor is intense and savory; the texture is dry and chewy. Pampanga specialty.</p>
<h2>Pair with Other Pampanga Stops</h2>
<p>Apalit pairs with Betis (the woodcarving town), Bacolor (the lahar-buried town), and Lubao (the historic church). A two-day Pampanga heritage circuit can cover all of them with the Apung Iru festival as the anchor weekend.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Day-trip from Manila is the easy option. Overnight stays in San Fernando or Clark with a car are alternatives if you want to fully experience the festival weekend.</p>
<h2>Crowd Notes</h2>
<p>The fluvial procession on June 28 is the densest. The June 29 and 30 days are calmer. The local provincial energy is family-friendly. Bring water, hat, and walking shoes.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Bus from Cubao to Cabanatuan or Tarlac; ask to be dropped at Apalit. By car, NLEX San Fernando exit then McArthur Highway south to Apalit (around 90 minutes from Quezon City).</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>June 28 to 30 only. The festival is not held at any other time. The third week of June is the buildup with novena masses.</p>
<p>Apung Iru is the small Pampanga river festival most travelers race past. A weekend in Apalit during the fluvial procession is the calmest way to feel a Kapampangan town tradition.</p>
