    // 39. CAMARINES SUR CHURCH LOOP
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.theladytravels.com/camarines-sur-church-loop',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Lady Travels',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'The Camarines Sur Church Loop',
        'slug' => 'camarines-sur-church-loop-bicol',
        'excerpt' => 'Camarines Sur has a quiet line of stone parishes from the Spanish era. Here is a calm one-day church loop from Naga.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Camarines Sur in the Bicol region has a quiet collection of Spanish-era stone parishes that most travelers race past on their way to Caramoan or Donsol. The churches were built by Franciscan missionaries beginning in the 1500s and survived earthquakes, war, and weathering. This is a calm one-day church loop from Naga, with notes on the buildings and the kwento.</p>
<p>The loop covers Naga, Nabua, Bato, and Iriga. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Basilica Minore de Nuestra Senora de Penafrancia (Naga)</h2>
<p>The Basilica in Naga is the seat of the September Penafrancia Festival, the biggest Marian devotion in Bicol. The Marian image was brought to Naga in 1710 and the original chapel was eventually replaced by the basilica. The structure is large, modern, and the interior is calm outside September. Free entry.</p>
<h2>Naga Cathedral</h2>
<p>The Naga Cathedral, the seat of the Archdiocese of Caceres, is one of the older stone parishes in Bicol. The structure has been rebuilt after damage from earthquakes. Free entry; modest dress.</p>
<h2>Porta Mariae (Naga)</h2>
<p>The Porta Mariae arch in Naga commemorates the Marian devotion to the Lady of Peñafrancia. Walk through the arch as a calm starting point of the loop.</p>
<h2>Nabua Church (Saint John the Baptist Parish)</h2>
<p>Nabua town has the Saint John the Baptist Parish, a stone Franciscan parish dating to the 1700s. The church is calm and the surrounding plaza is one of the older town squares in Camarines Sur. Drive 30 minutes south from Naga.</p>
<h2>Bato Church (Saint John the Baptist)</h2>
<p>Bato Church in the lake-side town of Bato also dates to the Franciscan mission era. The setting near Lake Bato adds to the calm visit. Around 45 minutes south of Naga.</p>
<h2>Iriga Cathedral</h2>
<p>Iriga is the larger town south of Bato and the cathedral of the Diocese of Libmanan-Iriga. The newer structure includes preserved colonial elements from the earlier parish.</p>
<h2>Buhi Lake Side Stop</h2>
<p>The town of Buhi, between Iriga and Bato, has Lake Buhi and the small church of San Antonio de Padua. The lake is home to the sinarapan (the world's smallest commercially-harvested fish). A 20-minute stop adds a natural-side contrast to the church loop.</p>
<h2>Penafrancia Devotion</h2>
<p>The Penafrancia devotion is the Marian tradition that dates to 1710. The image was brought from Caceres in Spain (after which Camarines Sur was named). The September fluvial procession on the Bicol River carries the image; the festival is the largest in Bicol.</p>
<h2>Bicol Food Pairing</h2>
<p>Pair the church loop with Bicol Express, laing, pinangat, and sili ice cream stops in Naga. The food trail in the previous post pairs naturally with this church loop.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly to Naga from Manila in one hour. Rent a car or hire a van for the loop day. The towns are spread south of Naga along the road.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>September is Penafrancia month; the basilica and the cathedral are packed. The cleanest months for the loop are December to May. Avoid Holy Week and the typhoon stretch (August to November).</p>
<p>The Camarines Sur church loop is the heritage day most Bicol travelers skip. A quiet morning in stone parishes is the contrast to the Bicol food and the Caramoan beaches.</p>
